text: Considering how much was Americanized (dumbed down) I was honestly really surprised Rita still had her axe.  Hilariously Rita is made blonde when she's actually a ginger in the book, which is something they actually joke about in the book.  Jackets look retarded and I hate their design, I much prefer the huge intimidating hulking monstrosities they're made out to be in the book and manga I also don't like how the protagonist is like a middle aged man and not the young recruit like it is in the book.  Mimics look absolutely nothing like they're made out in the book but I'm okay with that because I thought their design in the book was retarded  But in all seriousness, this does look like the director was genuinely trying to make a faithful movie, a lot of what I love about All You Need is Kill is still there but it looks like they changed a bunch of stuff to get it accepted which is fine because that happens with adaptations, there isn't a lot you can do to stop that.  I'm actually excited for this, I hope hollywood doesn't fuck it up.

text: *Sigh* I know that an adaptation is, well, an adaptation, and that you should expect for things to be different. . . but goddammit the f*cking ending.  In the book the ending was grim. The characters over came a great challenge, but it cost them dearly. Humanity as a whole get's set back a step or two. It doesn't feel like a victory, so much as them just¬†postponing the inevitable. They won the battle, and saved some lives, but no one really get's to be happy. It was a great stand alone book, with enough strings left that it could have great sequel, which worked out great because it IS getting a sequel (so there is that to look forward to).  I noticed that they changes certain aspects of the aliens, and how "time travel" works (in the book it's NOT time travel, in the movie it is). I first thought it was because someone (writer or director) just didn't read the book, or maybe just skimmed it, or maybe they just thought this changes would make the movie more simple. . . It was actually so they could have one of those "no one dies, every one get's to be happy" cookie cutter endings. In the movie humanity cripple the aliens greatly, and by the end they've(humans) pretty much won the war.

text: I think they should make a videogame adaptation of this film now, I know what you're thinking: "No videogames based on movies SUUUUUCK!" And, I somewhat agree.  But, it would be like an fps rogue-like with a story to explain the rouge-like elements. And the more the player finds out through each play through, the more they're able to branch out and explore the game's world. So the player won't know what's going on in 1 play through, then in the next they'll find out a different objective, and then in the next they'll find out another and another, etc., etc.. and that would just be awesome imo. Of course the replay-ability would stop as soon as the player finds out how to reach and kill the big bad boss, but still. It'd be neat to see playing through a game over and over again as a game mechanic... like rogue legacy or (I suppose) dark souls mixed with fps action. The more you know, the easier it is.  It'll probably never happen since people can just pump out call of modern¬†halofield 5 future warfare and probably get the same revenue as opposed to doing something new and awesome... but w/e. it's an idea.

text: Went to theater with low expectation, thinking its just another typical sci-fi action movie starring my favorite actress Emily Blunt and well, not a fan of, Tom Cruise.  Boy oh boy I was blown away, from the minute I sat down, until the finish I was very entertained and sucked into the movie! Went way way above my expectation, it may not be original but the plot and script execution is so damn good. The acting were awesome, Tom Cruise was awesome - probably his best movie yet, even when he's silence he told many stories just with his facial and pretty funny at times.  The supporting actors were amazing, not a lot of of screen time but you learnt so many things about them as the movie goes on thanks to the time-loop or time-reset I might call it. Its one of those movie that will stuck in your head and will be remembered for a long time.¬†  9.5/10 Highly recommended to all. - Even if you're not a fan of sci-fi action movie and.. Tom Cruise.

text: Man, this movie was awesome. ¬†I had decent expectations when I first saw the trailer and I knew that I would've been happily surprised like most of Tom Cruise's movies and boy was I right. ¬†I'm so happy that I got to experience this on the big screen because just like any other big blockbuster caliber movie, you gotta have that awesome huge movie theater experience to make this movie truly wonderful. ¬†It's so sad that they couldn't have marketed this movie better because it deserved so much more media than it ever got. ¬†If people actually took Tom Cruise movies more seriously, they'd be pleasantly surprised at how good they are! ¬†Besides the Mission Impossible franchise Cruise's other movies such as Jack Reacher, Oblivion, The Last Samurai, Minority Report, War of the Worlds, and even Knight & Day where he's the main character are all good movies that I would without a doubt watch again and again. ¬†Of course there were a couple of movies inbetween that didn't fit my taste but all the ones that do are surprisingly pretty damn good! ¬†So if you haven't watched this yet, do yourself a favor and enjoy what most likely will become one of your favorite sci-fi movies of all time because it's one of mine now.

text: When I first saw this trailer, I couldn't help but cry. I never understood why. Even after I watched the movie, I still always found myself returning to this trailer. Live, Die, Repeat. The entire concept of a man who was forced to do just that enthralled me. At the time, I was a cocky, delusional kid -- always blaming my family for the way my life turned out. The arrogance was only a facade for what I was too afraid to face: that, deep down, I was living a lie. I didn't know what I wanted to make of myself, that I was too afraid to admit that I was only a speck of what I perceived myself as. Blaming them was just a pernicious way I could relieve myself of the responsibility of forging for myself a better life.  Live, Die, Repeat. I was too afraid to start phase two. I finally understood that. Now, I'm just a delusional man in his twenties -- afraid to start phase three.
